  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Yeonou
  author: Lee Jae-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In days of old, I sat for this portrait,
    When spring still lingered in my dark brows,
    Two temples thick with youth's own verdant hue.

    How many years this image wandered far,
    Passing through countless hands and distant halls,
    Until at last we met again by chance.

    Yet here—the spirit dwells unchanged, unmarred.
    This thing before me is no other thing:
    My former self now stands as latter self.

    Strange how my children and grandchildren gaze
    Upon this face and do not know its truth,
    Asking again and yet again: "But who?"
    Who is this man that time has rendered strange?
  footnotes:
    - This poem is a meditation on a portrait of the poet himself, likely discovered after years of separation. The work explores themes of temporal flux, identity, and the paradox of recognition and estrangement.
    - The phrase '前身' (former body) and '後身' (latter body) carries Buddhist philosophical resonance, suggesting cycles of existence and transformation.
